        Official Singles Chart on 24/4/2020

        24 April 2020 - 30 April 2020

        The Official UK Singles Chart reflects the UKs biggest songs of the week, based on audio and video streams, downloads, CDs and vinyl, compiled by the Official Charts Company. The UK Top 40 is broadcast on BBC Radio 1 and MTV, the Top 100 is published exclusively on OfficialCharts.com. View the biggest songs of 2024 so far.

        Another week of chart mayhem to contend with. Annoyed that the insultingly generic "Breaking Me" is surging up the charts and surprised that "Level Of Concern", which I'll admit grew on me considerably, fell off the debut. Let's have a look, as ever (before this review gets marked as spam again and renders my efforts useless), at the new arrivals to the top 100.

        #100 - Surf Mesa, Emilee - Ily (I Love You Baby)
        So this appears to be coming off Tiktok which, to be fair, we can thank for Old Town Road, but also some pretty underwhelming songs such as Supalonely and Death Bed. And in this case we have a lo-fi hip hop type of sample with all its warmth sucked out of it by a standard four-on-the-floor beat with some tropical flavour, there's really nothing remotely interesting about this, it feels very cold and lifeless, it doesn't feel organic.
        strong 4/10

        #98 - Don Toliver - After Party [WORST OF THE WEEK]
        Now perhaps my ears are off but this just sounds like a mess. This is some of the worst production I've heard on a mainstream trap song in some time, the vocals are buried in a swirling mix of sounds which sonically clash which each other and render everything muddy and undiscernable. I don't mind Don Toliver's vocal delivery on some minimalist and slightly psychedelic production la Travis Scott, which is how he got on the map in the first place, but this really isn't on the mark for me.
        light 4/10

        #86 - Joji - Gimme Love [BEST OF THE WEEK]
        I'll admit I have heard this song before, and in fact I've been following Joji's career progression from the very start, and I have to say this is a great addition to his discography. It starts with vocal production and a style more reminiscent of his earlier work, somewhat lo-fi in nature and sung in a quite rough manner. This is a turn off for a lot of people, but I think it actually bounces off the cold space in the mix to really bring out the emotion in Joji's voice. This is combined with quite a propulsive groove, but it's the melancholic chord progression that wins me over. The song, however, collapses into an acoustic guitar lick somewhat reminiscent of the main melody from Radiohead's No Surprises, and then from there blossoms into an absolutely beautiful song with lavish strings and an ascending chord progression that genuinely feels heavenly and transcendent, Joji once again proves that he is one of the most interesting faces in R&B, and well, the first half of the song would probably rank quite low in his discography but the second half more than makes up for it, transforming a fairly by-the-numbers song into something truly beautiful. Joji's ambition is palpable and I'm really looking forward to the future with him.
        strong 7/10

        #76 - Tisto, Becky Hill - Nothing Really Matters
        This is ok, I'll take this any day over whatever Kygo is doing. I think Tisto puts a bit too much reverb in the mix, and I am not a fan of the "na na na" vocal riff that provides the song's melodic selling point. I don't like the dark, throbbing bass at the drop because I think it's too played out at this point. But the song has a decent vocal performance from Becky Hill and the percussive embellishments make the mix nicely rounded out, though I think it should be crisper and sharper. While this song does the technical things right, it feels undercooked.
        light 5/10

        #65 - Gerry Cinnamon - Head In The Clouds
        I didn't want to like this because I heard a Gerry Cinnamon song that charted a while back and it rubbed me the wrong way, but there is undeniable quality here. The guitar groove is good, the subtle increases in texture with the piano is good, the melody is sticky, Cinnamon's delivery is full of raw personality and his lyrics are actually really great and unique in the current mainstream. Perhaps if this had a hook it would pop more but I somewhat admire its restraint either way.
        very strong 5/10

        #51 - Playboi Carti - @ MEH
        I'm a huge Playboi Carti fan. Last year, with his album Die Lit, Carti redefined what trap could be with a series of repetitive and minimalist trap bangers that have undoubtedly pushed trap into new territory. I wsh the same could be said about his new song though, which seems to lack the same flair. Carti is undoubtedly more coherent here, but perhaps that's how he loses his main selling point. In Carti's music, his animated ad-libs and mindless lyrics merely supplement the blissed-out production, but here there's far less space in the production which draws more attention to his delivery. I would argue his delivery here is a bit too reminiscent of Young Thug's, I feel like Carti's unique trademark is lost. The production is ok, kind of glitchy and spaced out in composition but lacking the texture to pull it off. I don't mind this, but I expect better from Sir Cartier.
        light 6/10

        #38 - Nafe Smallz, M Huncho - Part Of The Plan
        This is pretty bad. I see 2 rappers with by-the-numbers Travis Scott impressions delivering nothing memorable over a swamped out beat with no texture. You'd think 2 rappers who rap melodically would be able to pull off something catchy over the space of this song but no. This screams of phoned in.
        decent 4/10

        #29 - DaBaby, Roddy Ricch - ROCKSTAR
        DaBaby is doing what he can over this production, but it's not enough. The chorus is pretty catchy but I just don't think the upbeat almost Latin-flavoured arpeggiated guitar sample is a good fit for DaBaby's fast and animated flows. The more melodic trap you listen to, the more you realise the entire game is indebted to Young Thug too, as here Roddy Ricch delivers a verse where he's really doing his best impression, and it's distracting.
        light 5/10

        #25 - Beth Porch - You Taught Me What Love Is
        A good singer is one who can command attention without the need for anything else, and this is what Beth Porch does here, over just a spare guitar. She has a powerful voice, and while this is a live recording so it is very rough around the edges, especially when she starts to belt in the second half of the song, there's such a raw emotion that coupled with the guitar, makes for a pretty good song.
        decent 6/10

        #20 - Sam Smith, Demi Lovato - I'm Ready
        This is an odd song, but I'm very surprised by how much it works. We're treated to a dark trap knock, something that took me completely aback when I saw the song's lineup and after having listened to both artists' recent output. Both Smith and Lovato deliver good performances with decent-enough lyrics. The chorus is a show-stopping, melodramatic plea into the void: "I'm ready for someone to love me" - it has all the hallmarks of a song that could fall flat on its face, but it doesn't, and with some tweaks to the production this could be great, it retains a uniqueness. This pushes both singers out their comfort zone, and they pull it off. I don't like everything, for example I would prefer a crisper mix and possibly some more interesting texture (the weird sample in the trap beat is a step in the right direction) but I'm surprised this even works at all to be honest.
        decent 6/10

        #5 - Live Lounge Allstars - Times Like These
        I do like this. The mix is so rich and textured, so lovely to listen to, so enveloping. Every artist does their bit, and that's what's this is all about. The composition is great. This is a lovely moment of coming together and making music. I don't love this, I think it is a slight touch too oversold at times, but I really like the sentiment and the instrumental texture is so deliciously satisfying.
        strong 6/10

        #1 - Michael Ball, Captain Tom Moore, The NHS Voices Of Care Choir - You'll Never Walk Alone
        I picked the wrong time to start reviewing, because what can you say about a song like this. What can you criticise? All I can say is this. I'm really glad that Captain Tom Moore has been given this platform, to sing his heart out over this song, in these odd times. Now listen, is this a revelation to listen to: no. But really a song like this transcends the 4 minutes and 10 seconds it's on, it's a cultural landmark, it stands to represent something greater which permeates the very fibre of our society. And as such an event, it's admirable. The production of the song is nice but for me, I don't like the choral elements. Michael Ball's performance is good. It's a nice song, but really what else is there to say? I'll leave it at that from me.
        strong "exempt from criticism"/10

        Fatigue really set in towards the tail end of this review so cut me some slack!! That was a lot of music!! But anyway, thanks for reading, and I hope you're all doing well.

        WEEKLY CHART REVIEW (24/04/2020 - 30/04/2020)

        So some people actually thought the charity single from Captain Tom Moore mightve lost its lead by today, but not me, with an 18k sales lead over The Weeknd on Wednesday night, I knew he was definitely getting that #1!

        Honestly, it might just be my favourite chart moment of 2020 so far! Im not saying its my favourite version of Youll Never Walk Alone by any means, but its the idea thats won me over. This is a cover of a classic that couldnt promote sticking together & friendship between others any better, so the fact that its gone to #1 in time of Captain Tom Moores 100th birthday is amazing enough to see, but its the fact that his efforts have helped raise over 28 million for the NHS at the time of this post has the power to save so many lives thats really warmed my heart! Of course, hes no stranger to saving lives, as hes also a former war veteran. Congrats to Michael Ball & the NHS Care Choir too, lets not forget them! Big respect for all of them, strong 8/10 here.

        Actually, while were on the topic of charity songs, theres a real chance that the Radio 1 live lounge song called Times Like These with so many artists on it could climb all the way to #1 next week, looking at those early sales numbers (already Top 5 overall after just 24 hours of tracking!). I wouldnt even rule out Blinding Lights going back to the top at some point in the future either!

        In fact, Ill discuss the two charity songs that entered right now! Firstly, weve got the Live Lounge Allstars, which features 24 massive global acts, covering a throwback from the Foo Fighters, who also appear here! Anyway, this is giving me all the motivation to keep going during lockdown. When previous campaigns in this lane were written, they were to support specific groups on people, but I think we can agree that this is a topic that affects everyone, so it would make sense to combine so many musical genres together & yet, every artist featuring on this gets the chance to stand out here, but the harmonies accompanied with a gentle twinkle & the melodic guitar strums are also impeccable! So yeah, absolutely wonderful & while its the kind of collaboration where replay factor may drop off fairly fast, for now, Im so chuffed to see this so high up already & its my favourite debut of the week! Strong 9/10 for this one.

        Secondly, thanks to her stunning BGT audition, Beth Porch makes her chart debut with You Taught Me What Love Is (#25). My whole family teared up when watching this last week! Not only are the soothing vocals & range so emotional, but the fact that she performs like this to unwell children & the connection a nurse has with them in making sure theyre better is another huge positive here. To be honest, if there was a little more swell on the guitar & dynamic in her delivery, this wouldve been another perfect score for me, but as it is, yeah, as someone whos worked with ill children myself, this really resonated with me! Light 9/10 for this one & she really shouldve got the Golden Buzzer!

        Outside of those, the biggest release of the past week was the collaboration between Sam Smith & Demi Lovato, called Im Ready (#20). Sadly, while I was excited to see the two names on the same song, Im rather underwhelmed by this! Ive known both of these to be very powerful singers when theyre at their best, but here, their vocal performance just doesnt reach a climax at all when youre expecting it to throughout the entire song! Not only that, but the chorus is repetitive & the whole topic behind the song is rather bland too, Besides, if you were really ready for someone to love you, shouldnt you have sounded more intriguing & made sure the production had at least a bit of sparkle & affection to it? Ultimately, its just really forgettable & I dont think much effort was put into it at all, sorry! Light 4/10.

        Then theres Rockstar by DaBaby ft Roddy Ricch (#28). Now we get to two trap artists who are among my favourite newcomers in the genre & wow yeah, this will definitely get some replay from me! The bubbling deep rumbles immediately set a serious scene, then DaBaby just comes out with one of his most fast-paced flows to date & his singing is surprisingly decent. Unfortunately, I cant say Roddy Ricch does as well here, but at least he still sounds sincere enough to fit in on this! Thats the thing, while the content isnt anything much of a progression, Im a lot more convinced when you actually sell it well, which I think mostly happens here. Its not the best rap hit here right now, but its still enjoyable overall as someone whos getting more into this kind of sound, so Im giving it a light 7/10!

        Then weve got a debut for Nafe Smallz & M Huncho with Part Of The Plan (#38) & sadly, given that this is the same duo that brought us the atrocity that was Thumb, I had no expectations that it would be good & much to nobodys surprise, I really dont like this! Neither artist sounds as hard as they think they do as theres way too much mixing on the auto-tune. Not only that, but despite them switching up their melodies, its done in a way thats so abrupt, theres absolutely no chemistry between them & the softer trap beats adds no substance nor groove to make this the slightest bit interesting! Light 3/10 here & as expected, the worst debut of the week.

        The last new entry of the week is Where Were Going by Gerry Cinnamon (#39)! Man, with all the support Radio 1 was giving this guy, it was only a matter of time before he made the Top 40 again, especially with an album boost for this. Anyway, I think this is awesome! The upbeat folk instrumentation & pure charisma of Gerry Cinnamon makes this immediately likeable even if youre not a fan of the genre, This genuinely reminds me of something the Gallagher brothers wouldve done with Oasis in terms of vocal delivery & while I wouldnt put Gerry Cinnamon anywhere close to their level of iconic quality, this is the kind ef song that gives home in difficult times, especially when you read the lyrics. Im giving this a light 8/10 for now, with the potential to climb!

        As for the albums side of things, its a little disappointing to see Dua Lipa drop from the top spot, but hey, Ill certainly take Gerry Cinnamon replacing her there.

        Thats it for today, but next week, apart from potentially more singles to combat Covid-19, rock had such a huge day of new music with The Rolling Stones & The 1975 coming back, along with a big resurgence for Foo Fighters, but whether or not they can stick around until this time next week is another question. Looks like KSI will get the highest debut of the week again with Houdini!

        Beyond that, stay safe & have a good weekend. :)

        Conner Harper
